---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const advisorBody = `
  

  <!-- ============ SECTION 0: HERO ============ -->
  <header class="hero hero--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-text">
          <div class="hero-eyebrow eyebrow">Financial Advisor Mortgages</div>
          <h1 class="display-1">Financial advisor mortgage from a lender who reads wirehouse W-2 grid commission, independent RIA AUM-based management fees, RSU stock awards at parent companies, forgivable loan recruiting structures, S-corp K-1 distributions, and practice book valuation as one income picture.</h1>
          <p class="lead hero-subtitle">Working U.S. financial advisors carry one of the most channel-bifurcated qualifying profiles in any sales profession &mdash; with the wirehouse-versus-independent-RIA distinction driving fundamentally different income mechanics, documentation patterns, and qualifying approaches. <strong>Per BLS OOH May 2024 data, personal financial advisors run a median wage of $99,580 with top 10% over $239,200. These numbers understate working top producers: established wirehouse advisors at Morgan Stanley (NYSE: MS), Merrill Lynch (subsidiary of Bank of America, NYSE: BAC), UBS Financial Services (NYSE: UBS), Wells Fargo Advisors (subsidiary of Wells Fargo, NYSE: WFC), Edward Jones, and Raymond James Financial (NYSE: RJF) commonly earn $250K&ndash;$1M+ through W-2 base + grid commission (typically 40-50% of gross production fees and commissions); independent RIA (Registered Investment Adviser) principals operating their own RIA firms earn $300K&ndash;$2M+ through S-corp combining W-2 reasonable compensation with K-1 distributions from AUM-based management fees (typically 0.75-1.25% of Assets Under Management annually); independent broker-dealer (IBD) advisors at LPL Financial (NASDAQ: LPLA), Cetera, Cambridge, Commonwealth, and Avantax operate hybrid 1099 commission plus advisory fee structures $200K&ndash;$800K; and elite top-producer advisors managing $300M&ndash;$2B+ of AUM at major wirehouses or as RIA principals commonly $1M&ndash;$10M+ annually</strong>. The qualifying mechanic that matters: aggregating wirehouse W-2 grid commission with parent-company RSU stock awards under B3-3.1-01 plus B3-3.1-09 for wirehouse files, or aggregating independent RIA S-corp W-2 reasonable compensation with K-1 distributions plus practice valuation balance sheet under B3-3.4-02 for RIA principal files, produces the actual income picture working advisors carry. <strong>Critical context: financial advisors are NOT eligible for Physician/Doctor Loan products &mdash; the optimal path is properly-structured Conventional Conforming or Jumbo with channel-appropriate documentation, supplemented by Bank Statement Non-QM and Asset-Depletion Non-QM as alternatives for post-practice-sale or high-deduction scenarios.</strong></p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Talk to Our Team</a>
            <a href="#income-methods" class="btn btn-secondary btn-large">See how financial advisor qualifying works</a>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-trust">
            <span class="trust-dot"></span>
            <span>Broker NMLS #1072866</span>
            <span>&middot;</span>
            <span>Specialist in wirehouse W-2 grid commission, independent RIA AUM-based management fees, RSU stock awards, forgivable loan recruiting structures, S-corp K-1 distributions, and practice book valuation for financial advisor mortgages</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="hero-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/7681091/pexels-photo-7681091.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1200" alt="Financial advisor meeting with high-net-worth clients to review portfolio" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1200x1500/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Financial+Advisors';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ============ STATS BAR ============ -->
  <section class="stats stats--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-bar-grid">
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$250K-$2M+</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Established working financial advisor income range from wirehouse advisor ($250K-$1M typical) through RIA principal ($300K-$2M+) to elite top-producers managing $300M-$2B+ AUM ($1M-$10M+)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">40-50% grid</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Typical wirehouse grid commission rate (advisor share of gross production fees and commissions); production bonuses on top; RSU stock awards from parent (Morgan Stanley, BoA, UBS, Wells Fargo)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">0.75-1.25% AUM</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Typical RIA management fee rate on Assets Under Management annually; recurring recurring revenue model produces stable income foundation as book grows</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">2 channels</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Wirehouse (W-2 at Morgan Stanley, Merrill Lynch, UBS, Wells Fargo Advisors, Edward Jones, Raymond James) vs Independent RIA (1099/S-corp with AUM-based fees) &mdash; the central qualifying classification</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="stats-bar-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/7681104/pexels-photo-7681104.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1000" alt="Financial advisor reviewing portfolio data" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1000x750/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Advisor';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ LEDE ============ -->
  <section class="lede-section">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="lede">Stairway Mortgage qualifies working financial advisors on the full income picture &mdash; <strong>wirehouse W-2 base salary plus grid commission (typically 40-50% of gross production fees and commissions) plus quarterly and annual production bonuses plus net new asset (NNA) bonuses for bringing in new AUM plus RSU stock awards from parent companies (Morgan Stanley, Bank of America for Merrill Lynch, UBS Group AG for UBS Financial Services, Wells Fargo &amp; Company for Wells Fargo Advisors) plus active forgivable loan recruiting balances at Morgan Stanley, Merrill, UBS, and Wells Fargo (typically 100-300% of trailing 12-month production paid as multi-year vesting incentive to recruit established advisors from competitors) under Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01 variable income with 24-month average plus B3-3.1-09 for RSU vesting; independent Registered Investment Adviser (RIA) principal S-corp W-2 reasonable compensation plus K-1 distributions covering AUM-based management fees (typically 0.75-1.25 percent of Assets Under Management annually) plus possible sub-advisor override on junior advisor production at the RIA firm plus product commission income for non-advisory product sales (insurance, annuities) plus practice book valuation reserves under B3-3.4-02 from Form 1120-S; independent broker-dealer (IBD) hybrid advisor at LPL Financial, Cetera, Cambridge, Commonwealth, Avantax with 1099-NEC Schedule C combining brokerage commission and investment advisory fees under B3-3.3-02 with 2-year averaging plus Form 1084 addbacks; branch manager override income at wirehouses for advisors promoted to branch leadership; Edward Jones IC W-2 model with branch ownership-feel structure; and post-RIA-sale earnout consideration plus rollover equity at PE-backed RIA consolidators (Hightower Advisors, Mariner Wealth Advisors, Captrust Advisors, Mercer Advisors, Beacon Pointe, Cresset Capital)</strong>. A new advisor in years 1-4 building book of business, an established wirehouse advisor at $250K-$500K, an established RIA principal at $400K-$1M, a top-producing advisor managing $200M+ AUM, and a post-PE-sale RIA principal each get qualified using methods that fit their actual structure. <strong>Working financial advisors are also key referral partners for Stairway Mortgage clients &mdash; many of our high-income clients first heard about us through their advisor recommending a specialist mortgage broker for their complex compensation picture.</strong> Or skip ahead: browse <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">every loan program</a>, run numbers on <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">100+ mortgage calculators</a>, or check <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/current-rates/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">today&apos;s rates</a>. For the parent hub and other sales professional paths, see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/sales-professionals/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">sales professionals mortgage hub</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #1: KEY FACTS ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 &middot; Financial advisor mortgage at a glance</div>
        <h2>Key facts every financial advisor should know before applying for a mortgage.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="key-facts-grid">
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Channel matters</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">The wirehouse vs independent RIA distinction is the single biggest qualifying variable. Wirehouse advisors receive W-2 grid commission qualifying under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a> with 24-month average. RIA principals operate S-corp structures with W-2 + K-1 under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.4-02</a>. Hybrid IBD advisors receive 1099-NEC under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a>.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">AUM recurring</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">AUM-based management fees (typically 0.75-1.25% annually) generate recurring revenue that builds as the book grows. For RIA principals with $200M+ AUM, recurring management fee revenue commonly $1.5M-$3M+ annually before considering performance fees, product commissions, or financial planning fees. This recurring revenue model produces stable income foundation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Series + CFP</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Required licensing: Series 7 (General Securities Rep), Series 63 (Uniform Securities Agent State Law), Series 65 (Uniform Investment Adviser Law for RIAs), Series 66 (combined 63 + 65), Series 24 (General Securities Principal for managers). <a href="https://www.cfp.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CFP (Certified Financial Planner)</a> credential from CFP Board is the premier financial planning designation; <a href="https://www.cfainstitute.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CFA (Chartered Financial Analyst)</a> from CFA Institute is the premier investment analysis credential.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Reg BI</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body"><a href="https://www.sec.gov/regulation-best-interest" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SEC Regulation Best Interest (Reg BI)</a>, effective 2020, established a "best interest" standard for broker-dealer recommendations. RIAs operate under the higher fiduciary standard of the Investment Advisers Act of 1940. The dual regulatory framework affects compensation structures and documentation but doesn&rsquo;t directly affect mortgage qualifying mechanics.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #2: ROLE-STAGE SOLUTIONS ============ -->
  <section class="professions-section section-tinted">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Where you are in your financial advisor career</div>
        <h2>Financial advisor mortgage solutions for every career stage.</h2>
        <p>Each stage of a financial advisor career has its own qualifying logic. A new advisor in years 1-4 building book has a different mortgage path than an established wirehouse advisor at $400K production, an RIA principal owning a multi-advisor firm, a top producer managing $200M+ AUM, or a post-PE-sale advisor with earnout and rollover equity.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="professions-grid">

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">01</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">New advisor (Years 1&ndash;4)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Recently licensed Series 7/63/65 advisor at wirehouse, IBD, or RIA building book of business. Production ramping with mentor or training program. May have completed CFP coursework."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $75K&ndash;$150K W-2 (wirehouse training tier)</li>
            <li>Or $80K&ndash;$140K Schedule C (IBD)</li>
            <li>2-year history not yet established for sole qualifying</li>
            <li>Conventional with W-2 documentation or co-borrower</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See new-advisor mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">02</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established wirehouse advisor</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established W-2 advisor at Morgan Stanley, Merrill Lynch, UBS Financial Services, Wells Fargo Advisors, Edward Jones, or Raymond James with consistent 2-year+ production. Grid commission + production bonuses + RSU from parent."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $250K&ndash;$700K W-2 grid + bonuses</li>
            <li>RSU vesting $25K-$120K annually from parent company LTIP</li>
            <li>Possible active forgivable loan from prior recruiting</li>
            <li>Conventional Conforming or Jumbo</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See wirehouse mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">03</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Established RIA principal / IBD advisor</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established RIA principal owning their own RIA firm with S-corp structure, OR established IBD hybrid advisor at LPL Financial, Cetera, Cambridge, Commonwealth, or Avantax with 1099 commission and advisory fees through Schedule C."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $300K&ndash;$1M+ S-corp W-2 + K-1 (RIA)</li>
            <li>Or $250K&ndash;$700K Schedule C 1099 (IBD)</li>
            <li>AUM-based management fees as recurring revenue foundation</li>
            <li>Conventional Jumbo with multi-source documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See RIA / IBD mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">04</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Top producer / Senior advisor</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Top-producing advisor managing $150M-$500M+ AUM at wirehouse or RIA. CFP plus CIMA/CPWA credentialing. Complex compensation across grid + production bonus + RSU at wirehouse, or AUM fees + sub-advisor override + practice value at RIA."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $700K&ndash;$2M+ across all components</li>
            <li>Substantial AUM base producing recurring fee revenue</li>
            <li>Multi-year practice equity at RIA or RSU at wirehouse</li>
            <li>Conventional Jumbo with multi-source documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See top producer mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">05</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Branch manager / breakaway / post-PE-sale</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Branch manager at wirehouse with personal production + branch override, breakaway advisor transitioning from wirehouse to independent RIA, or post-PE-sale RIA principal at Hightower, Mariner Wealth, Captrust, Mercer Advisors, Beacon Pointe, or Cresset Capital."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $500K&ndash;$3M+ with multi-entity complexity</li>
            <li>Post-PE-sale: cash + earnouts + rollover equity + W-2</li>
            <li>Breakaway: transition documentation across channels</li>
            <li>Conventional Super-Jumbo or Asset-Depletion Non-QM</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See branch / breakaway mechanics</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #3: INCOME CALCULATION METHODS ============ -->
  <section class="section" id="income-methods">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">03 &middot; The qualification mechanics</div>
        <h2>How we calculate qualifying income for your financial advisor mortgage.</h2>
        <p>Four methods cover almost every financial advisor file we&rsquo;ve closed. The right method depends on your channel (wirehouse vs RIA principal vs IBD hybrid), your career stage, whether you have made the S-corp election as an RIA principal, and whether you have active forgivable loan recruiting balance or post-PE-sale rollover equity.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Method 1 &mdash; Wirehouse W-2 grid commission + RSU (the wirehouse default)</h3>
      <p>The dominant pattern for established wirehouse advisors at Morgan Stanley, Merrill Lynch, UBS Financial Services, Wells Fargo Advisors, Edward Jones, and Raymond James. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a>, wirehouse W-2 base salary plus grid commission (typically 40-50% of gross production fees and commissions) plus quarterly/annual production bonuses plus net new asset (NNA) bonuses qualifies as variable income with 24-month average. Grid structures vary by firm: Morgan Stanley uses a payout grid based on trailing 12-month production with bonuses at production tiers; Merrill Lynch uses similar grid with NNA-focused bonuses; UBS, Wells Fargo Advisors, and Edward Jones use comparable structures. RSU stock compensation from parent company LTIP (Morgan Stanley RSU, Bank of America RSU for Merrill, UBS Group AG RSU, Wells Fargo &amp; Company RSU) qualifies under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-09/other-sources-of-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-09</a> with continuing vesting schedule.</p>

      <h3>Method 2 &mdash; Independent RIA principal S-corp + K-1 (the RIA default)</h3>
      <p>The dominant pattern for RIA principals operating their own Registered Investment Adviser firms. Under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/1361" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 1361</a> and <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, qualifying income combines S-corp W-2 reasonable compensation (typically $150K-$300K for RIA principal owner-operators) plus K-1 distributions from <a href="https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1120-s" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Form 1120-S</a> covering AUM-based management fees, possible sub-advisor override on junior advisor production, product commission income, and financial planning fees, all aggregated under 2-year history. Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks at the S-corp level recover non-cash deductions for office property depreciation, equipment, and amortization. RIA practice operations are generally classified as SSTB under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a> &mdash; financial services is on the SSTB list &mdash; with QBI deduction phase-out at higher income.</p>

      <h3>Method 3 &mdash; Independent broker-dealer (IBD) hybrid Schedule C (the IBD default)</h3>
      <p>For independent advisors operating through IBD platforms (LPL Financial, Cetera, Cambridge Investment Research, Commonwealth Financial Network, Avantax) with hybrid brokerage commission and investment advisory fee income. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.3-02/income-analysis-self-employed-borrowers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a>, IBD advisor Schedule C 1099 income qualifies with 2-year averaging plus Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks. IBD compensation structures combine brokerage commission (typically 85-95% net to advisor through the IBD payout grid after platform fees) and investment advisory fees (typically 0.75-1.25% AUM through the IBD&rsquo;s RIA platform). Independent advisors take substantial Schedule C deductions for office, technology platform fees, E&amp;O insurance, continuing education, CFP/CFA dues, marketing, and staff that Form 1084 systematically addresses for non-cash components.</p>

      <h3>Method 4 &mdash; Forgivable loan + multi-source recruit/retention structures</h3>
      <p>For advisors with active forgivable loan balances from wirehouse recruiting packages (typically 100-300% of trailing 12-month production paid as multi-year vesting incentive to recruit established advisors from competitors). Forgivable loans are structured as multi-year forgivable notes with annual forgiveness tied to continuing employment. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, annual forgiven loan amount creates W-2 income (the forgiveness is taxable wages) qualifying as continuing variable income during the active forgiveness period documented through the recruiting note terms. We document the forgivable loan structure with HR letter and the note documents showing forgiveness schedule and remaining balance. For post-PE-sale RIA principals, rollover equity vesting and multi-year earnout consideration similarly qualify under multi-source aggregation with proper documentation.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #4: DARK SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/7681104/pexels-photo-7681104.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 760px;">
        <div class="eyebrow eyebrow-light">04 &middot; What generalist underwriting misses</div>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper);">The income most lenders refuse to count on a financial advisor file.</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.78);">Six income facts that show up consistently on working financial advisor files and that generalist lenders typically either ignore, mis-categorize, or refuse to apply correctly. Each one is documentable; the lender just has to read the financial advisor channel-specific multi-source structure properly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dark-grid">
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">A</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Wirehouse grid commission structure (40-50% of gross)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Wirehouse compensation structures pay advisors a grid commission percentage of gross production fees and commissions, typically 40-50% net to advisor. Grid tiers escalate based on trailing 12-month production with higher payout at higher production levels. For a wirehouse advisor producing $1M of gross fees and commissions at 45% grid, W-2 grid commission produces $450K. Production bonuses, NNA bonuses, and quarterly/annual incentives stack on top. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-01</a>, full W-2 income aggregates with 24-month average.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">B</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">AUM-based recurring management fees</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">AUM-based management fees (typically 0.75-1.25% of Assets Under Management annually) generate the most stable recurring revenue stream in any sales profession. For an RIA principal with $200M AUM at 1% fee, recurring management fee revenue $2M annually before any new business. The recurring revenue model means established RIA principals have substantial baseline income that grows with market appreciation and new client acquisition. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.4-02</a> for S-corp RIA, the fee revenue flows through K-1 distributions with 2-year history supporting continuing income.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">C</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">RSU stock awards at wirehouse parents</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">RSU stock awards from wirehouse parent companies (Morgan Stanley NYSE: MS, Bank of America NYSE: BAC for Merrill Lynch, UBS Group AG NYSE: UBS, Wells Fargo &amp; Company NYSE: WFC) vest on multi-year schedules from new-hire grant and annual refresh grants. For established wirehouse advisors at top production tiers, RSU vesting commonly $50K-$200K+ annually from LTIP grants tied to production and tenure. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-09/other-sources-of-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-09</a>, RSU vesting qualifies with continuing vesting schedule.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">D</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Forgivable loan recruiting packages</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Wirehouse recruiting packages for established advisors moving from competitors typically include forgivable loans of 100-300% of trailing 12-month production. For an advisor with $800K trailing production moving from Merrill to Morgan Stanley, recruiting package might include $1.6M-$2.4M forgivable loan paid as multi-year vesting incentive forgiven over 7-9 years tied to continuing employment. Annual forgiveness creates taxable wages on W-2 qualifying under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">B3-3.1-01</a> during the active forgiveness period.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">E</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Practice book valuation (2-4x annual revenue)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">RIA practice books carry established M&amp;A valuation multiples driven by ongoing PE-backed RIA consolidation. RIA practice multiples typically 2x-4x annual revenue based on AUM quality, client retention, advisor tenure, and growth rate. For an RIA with $2M annual revenue, practice valuation commonly $4M-$8M. Active acquirers include Hightower Advisors, Mariner Wealth Advisors, Captrust Advisors, Mercer Advisors, Beacon Pointe Advisors, Cresset Capital, and many regional consolidators. The practice valuation supports balance sheet narrative for Jumbo and Super-Jumbo mortgage qualifying.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
