          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My AUM-based fee revenue varies with market performance. Does that affect 2-year averaging?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Market performance affects AUM values which affect fee revenue. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.4-02</a>, the 2-year average smooths market volatility. For RIA principals with established 5+ year practice history showing AUM growth across market cycles, the 2-year average produces representative qualifying income. We document the AUM history showing growth trajectory and client retention.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I make S-corp election for my RIA practice?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically at $300K+ annual net Schedule C income for RIA principals, S-corp election starts producing meaningful self-employment tax savings. S-corp election involves paying yourself W-2 reasonable compensation (typically $150K-$300K for RIA principal owner-operators based on advisory production and management duties) and taking remaining profit as K-1 distributions. Coordinate timing with your CPA. We model qualifying impact pre vs post S-corp election.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My RIA practice is being acquired by Hightower / Mariner Wealth / Captrust. How does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">PE-backed RIA acquisitions typically structure transactions with cash up front, multi-year earnouts (typically 3-5 years), rollover equity in the holding entity, and continuing W-2 employment as producing manager. Post-sale qualifying aggregates ongoing W-2 under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, rollover equity K-1 under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.4-02</a>, and earnout consideration with multi-year schedule documentation. Strategic timing: close mortgage BEFORE sale on established RIA history, or AFTER sale with multi-source post-acquisition picture &mdash; we model both.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates higher for financial advisors?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No &mdash; mortgage rates for financial advisors are the same as for any other borrower at the same credit profile, loan amount, and program selection. The qualifying mechanics determine outcome &mdash; not borrower industry. Wirehouse W-2 advisors and RIA principals both achieve strong Conventional Conforming and Jumbo outcomes at standard pricing when proper channel-specific documentation supports the file.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My RSU from wirehouse parent (Morgan Stanley / BoA / UBS / Wells Fargo) &mdash; how does that count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">RSU stock awards from wirehouse parent company LTIP grants qualify under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-09/other-sources-of-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-09</a> as other source of income with vesting schedule documentation showing continuing vest through at least 3 years post-application. For established wirehouse advisors at top production tiers, RSU vesting commonly $50K-$200K+ annually. We document grant history, vesting schedules, and projected continuing vest.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My RIA practice has $4M of M&amp;A valuation. Does that help qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Indirectly through balance sheet narrative for Jumbo and Super-Jumbo qualifying. RIA practice M&amp;A valuations (typically 2x-4x annual revenue) support net worth documentation. For RIA principals considering succession or partial sale, recent comparable consolidator transactions from Hightower, Mariner Wealth, Captrust, Mercer, Beacon Pointe, and Cresset provide market valuation evidence. The practice value supports overall financial picture even when not directly qualifying income.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My spouse is also a financial advisor or in financial services. How does that affect us?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Two-advisor or financial-services households produce strong joint qualifying when both spouses have established 2-year histories. Both files combine as co-borrowers with full B3-3.1-01 (wirehouse W-2) or B3-3.4-02 (RIA S-corp) or B3-3.3-02 (IBD Schedule C) analysis on each spouse. Combined household income from two established financial advisors commonly $500K-$2M+ supports $1.5M-$3M+ qualifying. Two-RIA-principal households also benefit from combined practice equity narrative.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I just received a new forgivable loan recruiting offer to move firms. How should I time my mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Strategic timing matters. Options: (1) close mortgage BEFORE the firm change using established prior-firm W-2 history (cleanest qualifying); (2) close mortgage AFTER firm change once new firm W-2 establishes (typically 4-6 months post-move) with new forgivable loan structure documented; (3) coordinate with new firm&rsquo;s recruiting note negotiation to ensure mortgage timing fits the forgiveness vesting schedule. We model the options before you commit to a firm change.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do generalist lenders sometimes refuse financial advisor files?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Six reasons: (1) channel-specific income classification confusion (applying wirehouse W-2 rules to RIA Schedule C or vice versa); (2) production bonuses classified as "discretionary not stable" rather than properly aggregated as continuing variable income; (3) forgivable loan annual forgiveness refused as "temporary recruiting income" rather than continuing W-2 wages during forgiveness period; (4) RSU vesting refused as "speculative future stock"; (5) AUM-based recurring fees treated as "transactional not stable"; (6) sub-advisor override at RIA principals missed. The income is all there and verifiable &mdash; the file just needs a broker who reads financial advisor channel-specific multi-source structure correctly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the IRS Section 199A QBI deduction affect me as a financial advisor?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Financial services is classified as Specified Service Trade or Business (SSTB) under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a>. RIA principals and IBD advisors face SSTB phase-out limitations on the 20% QBI deduction at higher income (2024 thresholds: $383,900 for joint, $241,950 single, fully phased out at $483,900 joint and $341,950 single). This is unfavorable vs realtors and insurance agents who are non-SSTB. Coordinate with your CPA on QBI optimization.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can a co-borrower help me qualify?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; co-borrower files combine W-2s, 1099s, Schedule C, and S-corp distributions from both parties. For new advisors in years 1-4 where income is still establishing, a co-borrower with stable W-2 income often substantially helps qualifying ratios.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My S-corp RIA has retained earnings. Are those usable as reserves?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Generally yes if accessible. S-corp retained earnings in RIA business accounts count as reserves if you have ability to distribute them. Documented via 1120-S Schedule L (balance sheet). For established RIA principals with 5+ years of accumulated retained earnings, reserve strength supports jumbo qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m considering acquiring another RIA. How does that fit with personal mortgage qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">RIA practice acquisitions typically run $500K-$10M+ depending on AUM size, retention, and growth. <a href="https://www.sba.gov/funding-programs/loans/7a-loans" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SBA 7(a)</a> financing up to $5M is common for smaller RIA acquisitions; larger transactions often use conventional bank business acquisition financing or PE consolidator structures. We sequence personal mortgage either BEFORE acquisition closes (qualifying on established RIA Schedule C / S-corp history) or AFTER acquisition integrates 12-18 months post-acquisition with combined-practice history.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My FINRA Form U4 has prior disclosures. Does that affect my mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Material FINRA disclosures or SEC IAPD (Investment Adviser Public Disclosure) findings can affect underwriting review. Minor compliance issues typically don&rsquo;t affect qualifying; material disclosures (customer arbitrations, regulatory actions) may require underwriting explanation. We coordinate any necessary explanation through your compliance department for context. Active licensure with current standing is the key requirement.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are there mortgage programs specifically designed for financial advisors?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No specialty advisor-specific products are widely available. What matters is finding a broker who understands channel-specific qualifying: B3-3.1-01 wirehouse W-2 with grid + RSU + forgivable loan, B3-3.4-02 RIA principal S-corp with AUM fees + sub-advisor override + practice valuation, B3-3.3-02 IBD Schedule C with Form 1084 addbacks, and the multi-source aggregation working advisors commonly require. Conventional Conforming and Jumbo done right outperforms specialty product chasing.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use bank statements alone instead of tax returns?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes through Bank Statement Program Non-QM products for high-deduction IBD Schedule C advisors or breakaway advisors with limited tax return history showing the new RIA structure. 12 or 24 months of business bank statements qualify under the Bank Statement Non-QM framework. Pricing carries 0.75-1.5% rate premium vs Conventional.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a top producer with significant liquid investment assets. Can I use Asset-Depletion?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; Asset-Depletion Non-QM qualifies on liquid investment assets amortized over 360 months as implied income. For top-producing advisors with $1M-$5M+ of liquid investment assets (often in personal brokerage accounts representing accumulated savings from years of advisor compensation), Asset-Depletion provides alternative qualifying path. Particularly useful post-RIA-sale with significant cash proceeds.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 120-150 days before you intend to make an offer. Financial advisor files benefit from substantial runway because of channel-specific income classification, multi-component documentation across grid + RSU + forgivable loan (wirehouse) or AUM fees + sub-advisor override + practice value (RIA), full Schedule C analysis for IBD advisors, possible S-corp 1120-S review for RIA principals, FINRA Series licensure verification, and any PE consolidator acquisition timing coordination if applicable.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What HR or compliance documentation should I request from my firm?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">For wirehouse advisors: HR compensation letter covering grid commission structure, production bonus criteria and history, forgivable loan note documents showing remaining balance and forgiveness schedule, RSU grant agreements with vesting schedules, and current employment verification. For RIA principals: Form ADV showing AUM and fee structure, custodial relationship statements confirming AUM, sub-advisor agreements if applicable, S-corp 1120-S returns with K-1s, and practice valuation documentation if recently appraised.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

