  <!-- ============ H2 #12: PRE-CTA CLOSING STORY ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="margin-bottom: var(--s-6);">
        <div class="eyebrow">12 &middot; What "right door first" looks like</div>
        <h2>Financial advisor mortgage, structured right.</h2>
        <p>Established wirehouse financial advisor at a major brokerage for 14 years with CFP and CIMA credentials managing approximately $185M of client assets across high-net-worth and retirement plan portfolios. W-2 base salary of $85K (modest base typical for established wirehouse advisors) plus grid commission of $385K (45% grid commission on $855K of gross production fees and commissions, reflecting the standard wirehouse payout grid structure at the advisor&rsquo;s production tier) plus annual production bonus of $85K (tied to multi-year production tier qualification with consistent qualification across the 8 years prior) plus net new asset (NNA) bonus of $35K (for bringing in approximately $18M of new client AUM during the production year through referrals and prospecting) plus active forgivable loan annual forgiveness of $115K (representing the annual taxable forgiveness amount from a 2020 wirehouse-to-wirehouse recruiting package of $1.5M paid as multi-year vesting incentive over a 9-year forgiveness schedule tied to continuing employment, with remaining 5 years of forgiveness through 2029) plus RSU vesting from parent company LTIP of $65K annually (from new-hire grant + 4 annual refresh grants over the 4-year tenure post-recruiting). Total W-2 averaging $735K over the 2-year period. Plus the advisor maintains CFP credential from the CFP Board and CIMA (Certified Investment Management Analyst) credential supporting the top-tier wirehouse advisor narrative. The first lender pulled the W-2 and applied 24-month average treatment but classified the production bonus as "discretionary not stable" despite the documented multi-year continuity, refused the forgivable loan annual forgiveness as "temporary recruiting income not continuing" despite the active 9-year vesting schedule with 5 years of remaining annual forgiveness, refused the RSU vesting income as "speculative future stock subject to market volatility," and offered the advisor $785K Conventional Conforming based on base salary plus standard grid commission at $470K qualifying income. They missed that wirehouse production bonuses tied to documented multi-year production tier qualification qualify as continuing variable income under B3-3.1-01, that forgivable loan annual forgiveness with documented forgiveness schedule and continuing employment requirement qualifies as continuing W-2 wages during the active forgiveness period, and that RSU vesting from existing LTIP grants with documented vesting schedules qualifies under B3-3.1-09 as continuing other income. We pulled the two complete W-2s showing the full multi-component variable income including the forgivable loan annual taxable forgiveness, the HR compensation letter from the wirehouse documenting the grid structure with multi-year production tier history and the production bonus criteria with 8-year continuous qualification documentation, the recruiting note documents from the 2020 transition showing the $1.5M forgivable loan structure with 9-year forgiveness schedule and remaining balance, the LTIP grant agreements documenting RSU vesting schedule for continuing vest through the next 4 years from existing grants, the FINRA Series 7/63/66 licensure verification through BrokerCheck, the CFP credential verification through CFP Board, and the personal pay stubs covering the most recent 30 days. Ran the W-2 variable income components under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue);">Fannie Mae B3-3.1-01</a> with 24-month average plus aggregated the RSU vesting income under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-09/other-sources-of-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue);">B3-3.1-09</a> with continuing vesting schedule documentation. Total qualifying income: approximately $695K. Approved at $1.45M Conventional Jumbo for a Weston home in 41 days. Multi-source wirehouse advisor income with production bonus + forgivable loan forgiveness + RSU vesting is the standard top-tier wirehouse advisor pattern &mdash; the first lender just didn&rsquo;t know how to read wirehouse W-2 multi-component structure with proper recognition of forgivable loan and RSU income.</p>
      </div>
